// core ‚Äî the compiler's IMPLICIT RUNTIME (always in scope, no `#import`). This is prepended to
// every program, so it holds only the symbols the COMPILER ITSELF emits on the user's behalf:
// the boolean constants the language uses, and `streq` (the `match` string-pattern desugar emits a
// bare call to it). User-facing library code lives in explicit, qualified stdlib modules:
//   os  ‚Äî raw syscall + fd I/O (open/read/write/close/lseek/exit)
//   io  ‚Äî `file` handle + file ops + whole-file mmap externs
//   fmt ‚Äî printf/sprintf/fflush + print/print_float + assert
//   net ‚Äî `socket` handle + TCP ops
//   str ‚Äî strlen/strcopy
// (Nothing a user calls by name belongs here; future compiler-emitted helpers ‚Äî panic/bounds/eq ‚Äî
// would join `streq`, never user library code.)

// `i32` is the canonical 32-bit integer; `int` is a TRANSPARENT (tier-1) alias of it ‚Äî the same
// type, freely interchangeable. Diagnostics read `i32` (the primary name).
int :: alias i32;

// `byte` is a raw unsigned 8-bit value ‚Äî a TRANSPARENT (tier-1) alias over the canonical `u8`
// primitive: `byte` and `u8` are the same type, freely interchangeable.
byte :: alias u8;

// Boolean type. Arche has no `bool` primitive; comparisons yield 0/1, so `bool` is a DISTINCT
// (tier-2) subtype of `i8`. Comparison operands stay lenient (`1 == true` ok), int literals flex in
// (`ok : bool : 1`), and a bool flows back out AS an int one-way (`bool`‚Üí`i8`). What it blocks: a
// named int silently becoming a bool (`int n := 1; bool b := n` needs `bool(n)`).
bool :: i8;
true  : bool : 1;
false : bool : 0;

// Byte-compare two strings: 1 if equal, 0 otherwise. Pure (no FFI). Lives in core because the
// `match` string-pattern desugar emits a bare `streq(...)` call ‚Äî it is compiler-emitted, not a
// user-facing library symbol, so it must resolve without an import.
streq :: func(a: []char, b: []char) -> bool {
  if (a.length != b.length) {
    return false;
  }
  for (i := 0; i < a.length; i = i + 1) {
    if (i >= b.length) {
      return false; // guard: makes b[i] provably in-bounds (a.length == b.length here anyway)
    }
    if (a[i] != b[i]) {
      return false;
    }
  }
  return true;
}

// The primitives a failure policy needs to crash: libc `_exit` (terminate; `_exit` not `exit` keeps the
// global name distinct from a device's `os.exit`) and `dprintf` (emit a diagnostic to a fd first ‚Äî
// `dprintf` over `write` so the symbol can't collide with `os.write` in the all-stdlib test harness;
// the messages carry no `%`, so it is a plain fd-write). The `own` is the FFI rule for array params.
#foreign {
  _exit   :: proc(code: int);
  dprintf :: proc(fd: int, own fmt: []char)(r: int);
}

// ===== failure policies =====
// A `policy` is a MACRO: the compiler inlines its body at a fallible op, with the op's operands bound
// as mutable locals (`len`,`i` for a bounds index/slice; `a`,`b` for a divide), then runs the RAW op
// on whatever they now are. So a policy mutates its operands and/or terminates ‚Äî nothing is built in,
// not even `abort`. An EMPTY body leaves the operands untouched ‚áí the raw op ‚áí that's `undefined`.
// These are the common ones; users write their own (`@policy(bounds) my_clamp :: policy(len,i){‚Ä¶}`).

@policy (bounds) abort :: policy (len: int, i: int) {
  if (i < 0 || i >= len) {
    dprintf(2, "arche: index out of bounds\n")(_:);
    _exit(134);
  }
}

@policy (bounds) clamp :: policy (len: int, i: int) {
  if (i < 0) {
    i = 0;
  }
  if (i >= len) {
    i = len - 1;
  }
}

// Modulo (ring/toroidal) index ‚Äî out of range wraps around. The double-mod keeps a negative `i` positive.
@policy (bounds) wrap :: policy (len: int, i: int) {
  i = ( (i % len) + len) % len;
}

// The empty policy: no mutation ‚áí the raw, unchecked access. `a[i] !undefined`.
@policy (bounds) undefined :: policy (len: int, i: int) {
}

// Divide-by-zero policies ‚Äî category `divide`, so they bind (a, b) = dividend, divisor. `abort` and
// `undefined` share their names with the bounds policies above; the op's category selects which.
@policy (divide) zero :: policy (a: int, b: int) {
  if (b == 0) {
    a = 0;
    b = 1;
  }
}
@policy (divide) abort :: policy (a: int, b: int) {
  if (b == 0) {
    dprintf(2, "arche: divide by zero\n")(_:);
    _exit(134);
  }
}
@policy (divide) undefined :: policy (a: int, b: int) {
}

// Pool overflow HANDLER policies ‚Äî category `pool`, invoked with `?` (`insert(P{ x: x }) ?reject`), not `!`.
// A full pool is an EXPECTED condition (reported via `ok`), not a bug, so a handler shapes the result
// rather than crashing. Operands are the prefix of `(count, cap, ok, slot)` the handler uses: `count` =
// live entities, `cap` = capacity (read-only); `ok` starts 1 (the insert writes iff it stays nonzero);
// `slot` is the write target (declare it to redirect the write ‚Äî eviction). The capacity check lives
// HERE, so an empty handler is a raw write. `reject` is the default applied to every pool.
@policy (pool) reject :: policy (count: int, cap: int, ok: int) {
  if (count >= cap) {
    ok = 0;
  }
}
